CyberSploit1

Target IP: 192.168.170.92

Scanning



Looks like there are two ports open on the target machine: HTTP and SSH. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.170.92/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt shows interesting information about the application, such as the robots.txt.


The webpage is displayed on port 80.

I viewed the source-code of the HTML page, and found an interesting information: username:itsskv.



The robots.txt contains a base64 string. After decoding the base64 string, I obtained the string cybersploit{youtube.com/c/cybersploit}. Could this possibly the password for the username itsskv?

Exploitation


And it is! After connecting to the SSH application using the credentials above, I gained a foothold on the machine as itsskv.

Privilege Escalation


Running uname -a shows the Linux kernel is 3.13.0-32-generic. And there exists a public verified exploit for this kernel version.


I downloaded this exploit on my machine, transferred it to the target machine, compiled it, and ran it to gain a root shell. Now I am root!

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine as itsskv.


The proof.txt flag after I used the local privilege escalation exploit.
